1
00:00:58,316 --> 00:01:00,307
<i>Emily!</i>

2
00:03:02,340 --> 00:03:04,638
You're the medical examiner?

3
00:03:28,500 --> 00:03:30,491
Mr. Rose?

4
00:04:28,393 --> 00:04:29,690
I'm sorry, Mr. Rose...

5
00:04:31,896 --> 00:04:34,330
...but I cannot state conclusively...

6
00:04:34,532 --> 00:04:39,469
...that the cause of death
was natural.

7
00:04:40,605 --> 00:04:42,903
Your daughter, she...

8
00:04:57,255 --> 00:04:59,246
Excuse me, Father?

9
00:05:00,091 --> 00:05:01,956
Father Moore.

10
00:05:03,361 --> 00:05:04,658
You'll have to come with me.

11
00:05:14,138 --> 00:05:16,606
- Father Moore!
- Will you plead guilty?

12
00:05:16,808 --> 00:05:19,368
- Tell us about the exorcism!
- Over here, Father Moore!

13
00:05:19,577 --> 00:05:22,774
We're at Crescent County Courthouse.
We show you Father Richard Moore...

14
00:05:22,981 --> 00:05:25,609
- <i>What about the parents?</i>
- <i>They're not talking to the police.</i>

15
00:05:25,817 --> 00:05:26,943
<i>Do we charge them?</i>

16
00:05:27,151 --> 00:05:29,346
<i>No. Even the priest admits</i>
<i>he ran the show.</i>

17
00:05:29,554 --> 00:05:31,181
<i>We need a Christian on this.</i>

18
00:05:31,389 --> 00:05:32,583
Preferably a Catholic.

19
00:05:32,790 --> 00:05:34,849
Somebody that knows this shit
inside out...

20
00:05:35,059 --> 00:05:38,028
...and who the public will see
as unbiased.

21
00:05:39,030 --> 00:05:41,294
We're going after a holy man here.

22
00:05:42,533 --> 00:05:44,160
Ethan Thomas.

23
00:05:45,203 --> 00:05:48,798
He's not Catholic, though.
Methodist, I think.

24
00:05:49,007 --> 00:05:52,465
But the guy practically lives at church.
Choir, teaches Sunday school.

25
00:05:52,677 --> 00:05:55,805
He's no choirboy in the courtroom.
I've seen him tear people up.

26
00:05:56,147 --> 00:05:58,115
He's a shrewd son of a bitch.

27
00:06:01,986 --> 00:06:05,717
All right, pull him off whatever
he's doing. He's lead prosecutor.

28
00:06:26,644 --> 00:06:30,410
There's ambition. She never stops.
She even works while she drinks.

29
00:06:30,615 --> 00:06:32,606
- Gentlemen, you know Erin Bruner.
- Of course.

30
00:06:32,817 --> 00:06:35,081
- Hello.
- I was so sure Van Hopper would fry...

31
00:06:35,286 --> 00:06:38,016
...but you proved me wrong, lady.

32
00:06:38,222 --> 00:06:39,519
The system worked, that's all.

33
00:06:40,958 --> 00:06:43,449
Gentlemen, you'll excuse us,
will you?

34
00:06:43,961 --> 00:06:45,724
Have you seen the news
about this priest?

35
00:06:45,930 --> 00:06:49,559
I heard something about an exorcism
gone bad, but I don't know the details.

36
00:06:49,767 --> 00:06:52,167
The DA charged him
with negligent homicide.

37
00:06:52,370 --> 00:06:55,771
They offered a very reasonable plea
bargain, but the priest turned it down.

38
00:06:55,973 --> 00:06:57,167
Do not ask me to take this...

39
00:06:57,375 --> 00:07:00,606
The archdiocese
specifically requested you.

40
00:07:01,279 --> 00:07:04,407
- Why me?
- They followed the Van Hopper trial.

41
00:07:04,615 --> 00:07:06,207
They think you're smart...

42
00:07:06,417 --> 00:07:07,816
...and convincing.

43
00:07:08,386 --> 00:07:10,479
They want you to ask the priest
to reconsider.

44
00:07:10,688 --> 00:07:11,882
Well, what if he won't?

45
00:07:12,090 --> 00:07:15,025
This sounds like a quagmire.
If I'm smart, I'll leave it alone.

46
00:07:16,160 --> 00:07:19,323
Erin, the Van Hopper case
got you back on the fast track.

47
00:07:19,530 --> 00:07:21,521
Once again, you're a rising star.

48
00:07:21,733 --> 00:07:25,294
- Chivas, neat, please.
- Tanqueray martini, dry.

49
00:07:26,371 --> 00:07:28,839
- What are you saying?
- I'm saying, you do this for me...

50
00:07:29,307 --> 00:07:32,037
...and the rising star keeps rising.

51
00:07:32,243 --> 00:07:33,471
The case is yours.

52
00:07:36,280 --> 00:07:39,181
And just how high
do I get to rise this time?

53
00:07:41,452 --> 00:07:43,750
I've been junior partner
for too long now, Karl.

54
00:07:43,955 --> 00:07:46,116
- It's not like other firms haven't called.
- Erin...

55
00:07:46,324 --> 00:07:50,192
I want my name on the door,
right next to yours.

56
00:07:53,164 --> 00:07:54,756
Okay.

57
00:07:54,966 --> 00:07:56,160
Try to get the deal.

58
00:07:56,567 --> 00:07:58,558
If the priest won't
and this goes to trial...

59
00:07:58,770 --> 00:08:01,238
...the archdiocese feels he could
be an embarrassment.

60
00:08:01,439 --> 00:08:03,339
So under no circumstances
is he to testify.

61
00:08:03,541 --> 00:08:05,907
No, of course.
If I'd put Van Hopper on the stand...

62
00:08:06,110 --> 00:08:10,103
...he'd be marking time on death row
instead of sunbathing in Miami.

63
00:08:10,314 --> 00:08:11,679
His tab.

64
00:08:36,974 --> 00:08:39,272
Good morning, I'm Erin Bruner.

65
00:08:40,378 --> 00:08:41,902
May I sit down?

66
00:08:43,648 --> 00:08:46,981
They brought the chair
for my public defender.

67
00:08:48,486 --> 00:08:52,946
I guess they left it when they decided
I wasn't going to kill myself with it.

68
00:09:01,632 --> 00:09:04,533
My firm represents the archdiocese.

69
00:09:06,237 --> 00:09:07,534
Yes.

70
00:09:08,039 --> 00:09:11,202
Yes, I was expecting them
to send someone.

71
00:09:12,243 --> 00:09:14,973
- Why did they choose you?
- I wanted this case.

72
00:09:15,179 --> 00:09:18,615
- So you like the spotlight?
- I'm used to it.

73
00:09:18,816 --> 00:09:20,340
I defended James Van Hopper.

74
00:09:20,918 --> 00:09:22,977
And now you've come
to further your celebrity.

75
00:09:23,187 --> 00:09:24,415
No.

76
00:09:25,756 --> 00:09:27,747
I'm here to make senior partner
at my firm.

77
00:09:30,862 --> 00:09:33,524
- Are you a Catholic?
- No.

78
00:09:33,731 --> 00:09:37,030
I'm an agnostic, I guess.
I'm not really sure.

79
00:09:37,235 --> 00:09:39,032
If you're not sure, then you are one.

80
00:09:41,138 --> 00:09:44,665
I don't think you're the right attorney.
I'll stick with my public defender.

81
00:09:44,876 --> 00:09:47,344
He can't get the DA
to get you a better deal. I can.

82
00:09:47,545 --> 00:09:49,376
I won't be making
any plea agreement.

83
00:09:49,614 --> 00:09:51,844
If you don't, the archdiocese
won't post your bail.

84
00:09:52,049 --> 00:09:54,108
You'll be stuck in here for the trial.

85
00:09:57,054 --> 00:09:59,284
Do you understand how long
they can put you away?

86
00:09:59,490 --> 00:10:00,684
It's been explained to me.

87
00:10:00,892 --> 00:10:04,328
The DA's office doesn't like it when
religion holds itself above the law.

88
00:10:04,529 --> 00:10:06,087
And this prosecutor,
Ethan Thomas?

89
00:10:06,297 --> 00:10:09,095
You're gonna need somebody
hungry and smart...

90
00:10:09,300 --> 00:10:11,063
...and aggressive
to even have a chance.

91
00:10:11,269 --> 00:10:14,796
What would your strategy be to defend
me against such a formidable man?

92
00:10:15,239 --> 00:10:17,434
- That depends.
- On what?

93
00:10:17,642 --> 00:10:18,973
On how you wanna be defended.

94
00:10:23,748 --> 00:10:27,149
What's your main concern,
other than staying out of jail?

95
00:10:27,351 --> 00:10:30,809
- Is it how you're being portrayed?
- I don't care about my reputation.

96
00:10:31,022 --> 00:10:32,853
I'm not afraid of jail.

97
00:10:35,393 --> 00:10:38,726
What I care about
is telling Emily Rose's story.

98
00:10:39,897 --> 00:10:42,365
I want people to hear
what only I can tell.

99
00:10:42,567 --> 00:10:44,228
And what is that?

100
00:10:44,435 --> 00:10:45,993
What really happened to Emily...

101
00:10:46,203 --> 00:10:48,103
...and why.

102
00:10:51,542 --> 00:10:53,737
If I let you defend me...

103
00:10:53,945 --> 00:10:57,938
...will you promise to let me testify and
tell the truth about what happened?

104
00:10:58,749 --> 00:11:03,277
And what is the truth you would tell?
That the ritual killed her?

105
00:11:03,888 --> 00:11:05,947
- Was it your fault she died?
- No.

106
00:11:06,157 --> 00:11:08,216
All right.
Then I'll let you tell her story.

107
00:11:08,426 --> 00:11:12,123
But only if you agree to let me do
whatever else it takes to win.

108
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:24,000
Upcoming jump scare (Minor)

109
00:11:30,982 --> 00:11:33,974
You're not used to
this kind of place.

110
00:11:34,785 --> 00:11:38,448
I'm sure our life is very strange
to you.

111
00:11:40,191 --> 00:11:42,182
Not so strange.

112
00:11:43,427 --> 00:11:45,827
I grew up in a little town.

113
00:11:46,030 --> 00:11:48,794
But our house wasn't as nice
or as big as this.

114
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:50,968
My mother, she raised me alone.

115
00:11:51,168 --> 00:11:54,035
She was a schoolteacher,
so we had very little money.

116
00:11:54,238 --> 00:11:56,468
What a wonderful thing to be.

117
00:11:57,274 --> 00:12:00,266
That was Emily's dream,
to be a teacher.

118
00:12:00,745 --> 00:12:04,146
That's why she went away
to the university.

119
00:12:11,522 --> 00:12:13,581
A lot of cats live here.

120
00:12:15,059 --> 00:12:17,186
There are...

121
00:12:17,395 --> 00:12:20,057
...11 now, I think.

122
00:12:20,264 --> 00:12:21,754
Emily always brought them home.

123
00:12:21,966 --> 00:12:26,733
Ever since she was a little girl,
she couldn't leave a stray abandoned.

124
00:12:30,508 --> 00:12:32,840
Before these troubles began...

125
00:12:33,044 --> 00:12:34,375
...was Emily a happy girl?

126
00:12:35,046 --> 00:12:36,536
Oh, yes.

127
00:12:37,481 --> 00:12:39,972
Before she went away
to university...

128
00:12:40,184 --> 00:12:42,982
...my Emily was so very happy.

129
00:12:45,022 --> 00:12:47,991
What is going on...? Girls!

130
00:12:51,128 --> 00:12:52,959
Mama.

131
00:12:54,999 --> 00:12:56,432
Is it...?

132
00:12:57,835 --> 00:12:59,234
It's a scholarship, Mama.

133
00:13:00,671 --> 00:13:03,401
They pay for it.
They pay for everything.

134
00:13:04,442 --> 00:13:05,875
This is your dream, Emily.

135
00:13:07,912 --> 00:13:09,641
You'll be leaving us.

136
00:13:11,048 --> 00:13:12,743
It's okay.

137
00:13:14,885 --> 00:13:16,750
I'll be okay.

138
00:13:17,455 --> 00:13:19,889
I'm gonna show this to your father.

139
00:13:28,032 --> 00:13:31,399
- Counselor. Thanks for meeting me.
- Sure.

140
00:13:32,903 --> 00:13:35,804
Can I buy you a drink, Mr. Thomas?
He makes an excellent martini.

141
00:13:36,006 --> 00:13:37,906
Just water for me, please.

142
00:13:38,509 --> 00:13:39,908
So...

143
00:13:40,111 --> 00:13:42,909
...the judge thinks we should offer
a new plea agreement.

144
00:13:43,881 --> 00:13:47,248
She feels the community might be
better served without this trial.

145
00:13:47,451 --> 00:13:49,578
How do you feel about it?

146
00:13:49,787 --> 00:13:51,448
Personally.

147
00:13:52,089 --> 00:13:54,523
My job is to represent
the interests of the people...

148
00:13:54,725 --> 00:13:56,386
...and make an effort to be objective.

149
00:13:58,863 --> 00:14:00,660
I ask because I know
you're a churchgoer.

150
00:14:00,865 --> 00:14:02,628
Now you're set to prosecute
a man of God.

151
00:14:03,200 --> 00:14:05,134
Your priest broke the law...

152
00:14:05,336 --> 00:14:07,361
...and a young girl is dead.

153
00:14:08,305 --> 00:14:11,502
If he's a man of God, then, personally,
I think he's even more subject...

154
00:14:11,709 --> 00:14:15,304
...to the laws of moral behavior.
If it were up to me, he'd get no deal.

155
00:14:15,513 --> 00:14:19,244
And forgiveness and compassion?
Isn't that part of your creed?

156
00:14:19,450 --> 00:14:21,418
Or does that just get in the way
of your work?

157
00:14:24,822 --> 00:14:26,983
If you have compassion
for your client...

158
00:14:27,191 --> 00:14:29,489
...you'll persuade him to accept this:

159
00:14:29,693 --> 00:14:31,991
Charges reduced
to reckless endangerment.

160
00:14:32,196 --> 00:14:34,289
Twelve months in a county jail.

161
00:14:34,498 --> 00:14:36,898
Reducible to six, plus probation,
if he stays out of trouble.

162
00:14:37,101 --> 00:14:38,762
Somehow I expect
he can manage that.

163
00:14:39,670 --> 00:14:42,969
But please understand me.
If he refuses, I will seek the maximum.

164
00:14:43,440 --> 00:14:46,204
Father Moore has made it clear
there will be no plea agreement.

165
00:14:46,410 --> 00:14:49,174
He will not lie or admit to something
he is not guilty of.

166
00:14:49,380 --> 00:14:52,872
- And he was never neglectful of Emily.
- "Never neglectful"?

167
00:14:53,083 --> 00:14:54,846
Have you seen
the postmortem photographs?

168
00:14:59,323 --> 00:15:03,020
We'll go to trial. My client wants
the public to know the truth.

169
00:15:03,861 --> 00:15:05,488
Good.

170
00:15:06,597 --> 00:15:08,428
So do I.

171
00:15:10,100 --> 00:15:12,159
Have a good night, counselor.

172
00:16:21,572 --> 00:16:25,201
Let the record show that the defendant
and his counsel are present...

173
00:16:25,409 --> 00:16:27,070
...and that the jury is seated.

174
00:16:27,678 --> 00:16:31,409
- Mr. Thomas, you may begin.
- Thank you, Your Honor.

175
00:16:31,615 --> 00:16:34,675
Good morning, ladies and gentlemen.
My name is Ethan Thomas.

176
00:16:34,885 --> 00:16:38,286
I'm the assistant district attorney,
and I represent the people.

177
00:16:38,489 --> 00:16:40,889
In the case before you,
the evidence will show...

178
00:16:41,091 --> 00:16:45,755
...that the victim had a serious medical
condition that demanded treatment.

179
00:16:45,963 --> 00:16:50,161
We will prove that the victim's
condition rendered her physically...

180
00:16:50,367 --> 00:16:55,327
...and psychologically incapable
of caring for herself.

181
00:16:55,539 --> 00:16:57,029
Her care...

182
00:16:57,241 --> 00:16:58,936
...was then wholly entrusted...

183
00:16:59,476 --> 00:17:03,310
...to that man, the defendant,
Father Richard Moore.

184
00:17:03,514 --> 00:17:06,108
She became his responsibility...

185
00:17:07,117 --> 00:17:09,950
...and he betrayed
that responsibility...

186
00:17:10,154 --> 00:17:12,645
...by persuading her to abandon
her medical treatment...

187
00:17:12,856 --> 00:17:15,347
...in favor of religious treatment:

188
00:17:16,093 --> 00:17:19,688
A ritual exorcism,
performed by the defendant...

189
00:17:19,897 --> 00:17:24,834
...allegedly to cure the victim
by ridding her of demonic forces.

190
00:17:25,502 --> 00:17:29,131
We will demonstrate
that this course of action...

191
00:17:29,340 --> 00:17:32,275
...directly resulted
in the victim's death.

192
00:17:33,210 --> 00:17:35,405
I said a moment ago
that I represent the people.

193
00:17:35,612 --> 00:17:38,638
We all know what that means,
but it's a little abstract, isn't it?

194
00:17:39,183 --> 00:17:41,344
Miss Bruner,
the attorney for the defense...

195
00:17:41,552 --> 00:17:44,385
...is seated right next
to the man she represents.

196
00:17:44,588 --> 00:17:47,887
And I stand here
to represent the people.

197
00:17:49,393 --> 00:17:51,327
That's not really why
I stand here today.

198
00:17:52,563 --> 00:17:56,021
I'm here on behalf of someone
who can't sit at a table...

199
00:17:57,234 --> 00:18:00,465
...and look at you every day
and gain your sympathy...

200
00:18:01,138 --> 00:18:03,868
...someone who can't take the stand
to testify...

201
00:18:04,074 --> 00:18:07,407
...and tell you what happened
in her own words.

202
00:18:09,747 --> 00:18:11,214
A young girl...

203
00:18:11,415 --> 00:18:13,349
...that could've been your daughter.

204
00:18:14,184 --> 00:18:15,845
Could've been mine.

205
00:18:16,053 --> 00:18:19,955
A girl who trusted
Father Richard Moore with her life.

206
00:18:26,897 --> 00:18:28,228
This is what she looked like...

207
00:18:31,502 --> 00:18:35,802
...before the defendant began
his religious treatment.

208
00:18:38,375 --> 00:18:42,141
This is a photograph taken of her
on the day that she died.

209
00:18:56,193 --> 00:19:00,527
I stand here for Emily Rose...

210
00:19:02,299 --> 00:19:04,597
...who died horribly...

211
00:19:05,636 --> 00:19:07,831
...at age 19.

212
00:19:09,807 --> 00:19:13,436
You won't be able to see Emily sitting
here day after day during this trial.

213
00:19:13,944 --> 00:19:16,708
But I hope you'll remember her
as she was when she was alive...

214
00:19:18,582 --> 00:19:20,072
...and full of...

215
00:19:21,518 --> 00:19:24,282
...hopes and dreams.

216
00:19:26,256 --> 00:19:30,158
And as she was when Father
Richard Moore was finished with her...

217
00:19:31,428 --> 00:19:32,918
...and left her to die.

218
00:19:36,233 --> 00:19:37,928
Thank you.

219
00:19:38,902 --> 00:19:42,133
Is the defense prepared
to make its opening statement?

220
00:19:45,109 --> 00:19:47,168
I'd like to reserve
my opening statement...

221
00:19:47,377 --> 00:19:49,607
...until the presentation
of the defense's case.

222
00:19:49,813 --> 00:19:51,576
As is your privilege.

223
00:19:52,182 --> 00:19:54,446
Prosecution may begin.

224
00:19:54,651 --> 00:19:56,118
That was already my plan.

225
00:19:56,320 --> 00:19:58,811
Thank you, Your Honor.
The people call Dr. Edith Vogel.

226
00:19:59,022 --> 00:20:03,755
I've known Emily her entire life.
I took care of all of the Rose girls.

227
00:20:03,961 --> 00:20:06,987
Can you describe Emily
as you knew her growing up?

228
00:20:07,197 --> 00:20:09,529
She was a bit sickly
in her early years.

229
00:20:09,733 --> 00:20:14,329
She stayed inside a lot,
reading, learning music.

230
00:20:14,872 --> 00:20:16,533
How did she feel about
going to school?

231
00:20:16,740 --> 00:20:18,708
Objection.
The witness is not a psychiatrist.

232
00:20:18,909 --> 00:20:22,037
I'll rephrase. Did you talk to Emily
about going off to college?

233
00:20:22,246 --> 00:20:24,737
Yes. She told me she was excited...

234
00:20:24,948 --> 00:20:29,408
...but nervous that she would be away
from her family in the big city.

235
00:20:29,620 --> 00:20:31,611
This was an overwhelming change
for her.

236
00:20:31,822 --> 00:20:33,653
Did you stay in touch
after she went away?

237
00:20:33,857 --> 00:20:39,261
Yes. She wrote me a letter
saying that she'd been to a dance...

238
00:20:39,463 --> 00:20:41,488
...and she'd met a boy
named Jason.

239
00:20:41,899 --> 00:20:43,764
She didn't want her mother
to know this...

240
00:20:43,967 --> 00:20:46,458
...because her mother did not
approve of dancing...

241
00:20:46,670 --> 00:20:48,729
...and had warned her
about the boys at school.

242
00:20:48,939 --> 00:20:52,670
Did Emily communicate with you again
last fall after you received the letter?

243
00:20:52,876 --> 00:20:54,468
Actually, it was her mother.

